      "text": "SYSTEM DESIGN GUIDELINES\n\nHow to Approach System Design round - \n  1. Functional Requirements\n  2. Non-Functional Requirements\n  3. Core Entities - Actors in your system\n  4. API Contract with Input Parameters and Output\n  5. Data Flow if required - high level sequence of actions to be performed on the inputs to produce the desired outputs\n  6. High Level Design\n  7. Dive Deep\n\nFunctional Requirements \n    1. These are requirements that makes the system work. \n    2. Try to list 3-4 requirements, speak with your interviewer to confirm and start the high level design, satisfying these requirements.\n    3. Example such as booking a ticket for a concert is a functional requirement of a ticketing system.\n\nNon-Functional Requirements \n     1. These are requirements that would make a system faster and prone to failures.  \n     2. Try to list 3-4 requirements, speak with your interviewer to confirm and start modifying the high level design to satisfy these requirements\n\nCAP Theorem - which translated to Consistency, Availability and Partial Tolerance\n    1. Consistency - \n        1. Strong Consistency - All nodes should receive the same data when queried - This is called . \n           Example: If a user is in the process of adding an item to the cart (say there are only 2 items), \n           all the other users who queried in the that time slot should see just updated inventory. \n       2. Eventual Consistency - If a node writes a data, the data will eventually propagate to other nodes.\n           Example: If a user updated its profile picture, the updated picture will eventually propagate to other nodes. It need not be instant.\n    2.  Availability - This is very similar to eventual consistency where nodes might not require to see the updated data immediately \n          but at least return any result. For every request, there would be a response.\n    3. Partition Tolerance - Partition tolerance means the system should work even though there is network failures between nodes.\n         Why there exist a need to have network calls between nodes of the server ?  It may be because they share a state.\n         If they share the state, to achieve partition tolerance, we can persist the state in a database or cache ? \n         Partition tolerance is a must for a distributed system.\n \n\n1. Every system design will have multiple use-cases where you have to select between consistency and availability for a use-case\n    (2/3 of CAP theorem - Partition Tolerance is permanent but consistency and availability is a choice per use-case)\n      a. 'Booking a ticket in a concert' use-case should be strongly consistent. \n       b. However, 'seeing new concert details' use-case can eventually propagate to other users when added (eventual consistency)\n2. Latency - Every System should execute its workflow as quick as possible\n3. Scalability - Every System should be able to vertically scale (bigger machines with better CPU resources) \n                          and horizontally scale (more instances of the system) with an intent to handle more TPS\n4. Data Loss - Is it okay for your system to lose data ?\n5. Single Point of failure - System should be fault tolerant to single point of failure. \n",
      "fontSize": 42.01163853219831,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "SYSTEM DESIGN GUIDELINES\n\nHow to Approach System Design round - \n  1. Functional Requirements\n  2. Non-Functional Requirements\n  3. Core Entities - Actors in your system\n  4. API Contract with Input Parameters and Output\n  5. Data Flow if required - high level sequence of actions to be performed on the inputs to produce the desired outputs\n  6. High Level Design\n  7. Dive Deep\n\nFunctional Requirements \n    1. These are requirements that makes the system work. \n    2. Try to list 3-4 requirements, speak with your interviewer to confirm and start the high level design, satisfying these requirements.\n    3. Example such as booking a ticket for a concert is a functional requirement of a ticketing system.\n\nNon-Functional Requirements \n     1. These are requirements that would make a system faster and prone to failures.  \n     2. Try to list 3-4 requirements, speak with your interviewer to confirm and start modifying the high level design to satisfy these requirements\n\nCAP Theorem - which translated to Consistency, Availability and Partial Tolerance\n    1. Consistency - \n        1. Strong Consistency - All nodes should receive the same data when queried - This is called . \n           Example: If a user is in the process of adding an item to the cart (say there are only 2 items), \n           all the other users who queried in the that time slot should see just updated inventory. \n       2. Eventual Consistency - If a node writes a data, the data will eventually propagate to other nodes.\n           Example: If a user updated its profile picture, the updated picture will eventually propagate to other nodes. It need not be instant.\n    2.  Availability - This is very similar to eventual consistency where nodes might not require to see the updated data immediately \n          but at least return any result. For every request, there would be a response.\n    3. Partition Tolerance - Partition tolerance means the system should work even though there is network failures between nodes.\n         Why there exist a need to have network calls between nodes of the server ?  It may be because they share a state.\n         If they share the state, to achieve partition tolerance, we can persist the state in a database or cache ? \n         Partition tolerance is a must for a distributed system.\n \n\n1. Every system design will have multiple use-cases where you have to select between consistency and availability for a use-case\n    (2/3 of CAP theorem - Partition Tolerance is permanent but consistency and availability is a choice per use-case)\n      a. 'Booking a ticket in a concert' use-case should be strongly consistent. \n       b. However, 'seeing new concert details' use-case can eventually propagate to other users when added (eventual consistency)\n2. Latency - Every System should execute its workflow as quick as possible\n3. Scalability - Every System should be able to vertically scale (bigger machines with better CPU resources) \n                          and horizontally scale (more instances of the system) with an intent to handle more TPS\n4. Data Loss - Is it okay for your system to lose data ?\n5. Single Point of failure - System should be fault tolerant to single point of failure. \n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
