      "text": "TECHNOLOGY CONCEPT\n\nDistributed Locks - \n    1. Achieving Strong Consistency via Distributed Locks is a good solution. \n    2. For example if there are multiple instances of the booking platform where customers book tickets for a show, \n    its good to have a redis's distributed lock to hold a seat as locked while the user is confirming and making a payment. \n    3. Once the seat is locked, it will reflect the same to other users. If the user decides to not make a payment, distributed locks\n    have an ability to expire after certain time (TTL) post which, it will reflect as available to other users.\n\nDistributed Caches Strategy - The core trade-off is caches make reads faster but they introduce complexity around staleness and invalidation.\n      1. Write-Through Cache: Writes data to both the cache and the underlying datastore simultaneously. \n           Ensures strong consistency but can be slower for write operations. Useful for critical data.\n           If you write-through-cache, you can read-through-cache also as both of them are synced.\n       2. Write-Around Cache: Writes data directly to the datastore, bypassing the cache. \n           Here, read-though-cache can lead to stale data as db and cache are not synced yet.\n       3. Write-Back Cache: Writes data to the cache and then asynchronously writes the data to the datastore. \n           Useful for non-critical data, eventual consistency and high write throughput.\n       4. To tackle invalidation, we can use cache key with versioning which should match the database versioning. In this way, we don't have\n           to explicitly update the old cache entry and it will slowly gets deleted due to less frequency.\n       5. NOTE: Use distributed cache if all the servers see a similar pattern of request. If every server has an individual pattern of request, \n            consider in-memory caching\n\nLoad Balancers - \n    1. Useful to distribute load evenly to multiple instances of the server (horizontally scaled).\n    2. There are 5 different algorithms - \n    3. Round Robin - \n         a. Load Balancer simply route the request to the next server in a cyclic way. \n         b. All the servers will get equal load.\n         c. What happens if few instances of the server are more powerful than the other ones ? Ideally, powerful ones should get more request than other ones.\n    4. Least Connected -\n         a. The load balancer will maintain a state in its memory to track the transaction/connection allocated to each server instance.\n         b. It will route the transactions/requests to the least connected server.\n         c. If the S1 has reached 8/10 transactions per second and S2 also reach 9/10 transactions per second and S3 has reached 5/10, it will redirect to S3.\n    5. Weighted Round Robin / Weighted Least Connection - \n         a. Each Server will be assigned a weight based on its capability. The weight can be assigned statically or dynamically.\n         b. For dynamic weights, load balancers have to periodically check the health of the servers to understand their system conditions (such as CPU load)\n         c. Each server will assigned a weight percentage W(i)/W(T) where i = instance and T = total.\n         d. The max TPS on each server will be calculated as  [W(i)/W(T) * maxTPS on Load Balancer].\n         e. Example - Powerful server S1 will have weight 5, S2 and S3 will have 2 and 3 respectively. If the max TPS on load balancer is 100, then max TPS of \n                        S1 will be [5/10 * 100] = 50, S2 = [2/10 * 100] = 20 and S3 = [3/10 * 100] = 30.\n         f. The load balancer will maintain a state in its memory to track the transaction/requests allocated to each server instance.\n         g. If the S1 has reach 40/50, which means 0.8 and S2 also reach 10/20, which means 0.5 and S3 has reached 10/30, which means 0.33, \n             it will redirect to S3 as it has the least connections as per its capability.\n   6. IP Hashing -\n         a. Based on the client IP address, the load balancer will [hash(client-ip-address) % 2^32] and then route the request to the server close to the number.\n         b. The server location in the hash ring would be [hash(node-ip-address) % 2^32].\n         c. This is exactly similar to the shardingh concept where we use consistent hashing in a hash ring.\n   7. Least Response Time - \n        a. The load balancer will maintain a state of average response time of all the servers.\n        b. It will find the min of the response time and route the request to that server.\n        c. In doing so, it may happen all the requests are going to that 1 server.\n        d. To prevent it from happening, we can assign a weight to each of the server similar to Weighted round robin concept.\n        e. Instead of finding the minimum of average response time, we will find the minimum of average response time (i) / Weight(i) where i = instance of the server\n           and then route the request.\n\nRate Limiter - (Routing Service --> Rate Limiter --> Message Broker --> Load Balancer --> Micro-service)\n    1. First the request will go to the routing the service to identify the microservice\n    2. Once micro-service identified, we will create a cache with key = service_id and value as <counter> in Redis.\n    3. If the TPS allowed is 50, we will increment the counter till 50 within that second.\n    4. We will remove the cached key after the second (which is TTL)\n    5. If redis successfully increments the counter of the cache key, we proceed to allow-list the request to the correct service.\n    6. If redis fails, we will throttle the traffic using a message broker.\n    7. It can also preserve idempotency in use-cases like fraud-detection (bot clicking multiple times to fool ad aggregation service)\n\n\nMessage Broker (Queue based)\n    1. Producer send messages to the queue and a single consumer retrieves the message from the queue. other consumers don't receive the same message (1:1)\n    2. If there are multiple consumers consuming the same message at the same time, you can use distributed lock to mimic visibility timeout. \n    3. Consumer is responsible for pulling the message and can process at its own speed.\n    4. If we horizontally scale a message broker, we are basically creating more servers under the hood with each server having storage disks\n        and the server with less load should get the incoming request (or it is decided by some load balancing algorithm)\n\n\nMessage Broker (Pub/Sub Based)\n    1. Producer sends a message to a topic/group and all the consumer who are subscribed to the topic receives the message (Fan Out 1:N)\n    2. Consumer just keeps on receiving the message. If it is down, it is lost. (Not poll-based)\n    3. Pub/Sub usually means a message is short-lived, but it also remains in the disk and follows the logical data structure of a queue.\n    4. If we horizontally scale a message broker, we are basically creating more servers under the hood with each server having storage disks\n        and the server with less load should get the incoming request (or it is decided by some load balancing algorithm)\n\n\nMessage Event Stream\n    1. Publisher writes message and partition key. Using consistent hashing, partition key is used to find the right shard. These messages are written in log-based disk file \n        for that shard server.\n    2. All consumers are eligible to receive the message (similar to SNS) or can use poll-based mechanism (Similar to SQS).\n        All consumers keeps track of last message read as message is not deleted after retrieval. \n    3. Since the events are ordered, if we horizontally scale a stream, we have to create more servers of the streams (shards) and apply consistent hashing on partition key \n        so that the messages go to right shard and append to the log-based disk file.\n\nMessage Event Stream Aggregator\n    1. Aggregator reads from event streams and aggregates in memory for a fixed period of window, then outputs to Database. \n        For Durability, aggregator does persist data in disk.\n    2. If event streams are scaled to multiple shards, aggregator can also scale to multiple shards but scaling is less or equal to event streams.\n    3. Aggregator can read data comfortably from streams whose throughput is maxed out. This is because streams throughput involves writing to disks whereas\n        Aggregator reads and store them in memory for aggregation.\n    4. Aggregator persist checkpoint of streaming events in disk (S3). So, in case of crash, it looses its in-memory state, so it starts to read the events from the stream\n        from that particular checkpoint and aggregates in memory.\n\nSearch Optimized Database \n     1. When we add a document to such database, it goes to 1 shard based on partition key (consistent hashing). That shard is responsible for persisting the document\n         in the log-based disk file, in memory, replicate to slave shards, modify the inverted index and return success.\n     2. It is best for read heavy. Relax replication to slave shards to relax consistency is needed.\n     3. It uses Lucene as its underlying search algorithm for a particular shard. When we search the database using a word, every shard lookup for that word in its \n         Lucene's inverted index,  gathers all the data and provide to node for aggregating all results and produce the output.\n    4. Any updates to existing record/document creates a new entry in disk and marks the old one as deleted.\n    5. If you have smaller data set, rely on SQL for full table scan using LIKE command\n\nJob Scheduler\n    1. Schedule jobs via CRON command for every message (Event Bridge)\n       \n\n",
      "fontSize": 39.37675015425612,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "TECHNOLOGY CONCEPT\n\nDistributed Locks - \n    1. Achieving Strong Consistency via Distributed Locks is a good solution. \n    2. For example if there are multiple instances of the booking platform where customers book tickets for a show, \n    its good to have a redis's distributed lock to hold a seat as locked while the user is confirming and making a payment. \n    3. Once the seat is locked, it will reflect the same to other users. If the user decides to not make a payment, distributed locks\n    have an ability to expire after certain time (TTL) post which, it will reflect as available to other users.\n\nDistributed Caches Strategy - The core trade-off is caches make reads faster but they introduce complexity around staleness and invalidation.\n      1. Write-Through Cache: Writes data to both the cache and the underlying datastore simultaneously. \n           Ensures strong consistency but can be slower for write operations. Useful for critical data.\n           If you write-through-cache, you can read-through-cache also as both of them are synced.\n       2. Write-Around Cache: Writes data directly to the datastore, bypassing the cache. \n           Here, read-though-cache can lead to stale data as db and cache are not synced yet.\n       3. Write-Back Cache: Writes data to the cache and then asynchronously writes the data to the datastore. \n           Useful for non-critical data, eventual consistency and high write throughput.\n       4. To tackle invalidation, we can use cache key with versioning which should match the database versioning. In this way, we don't have\n           to explicitly update the old cache entry and it will slowly gets deleted due to less frequency.\n       5. NOTE: Use distributed cache if all the servers see a similar pattern of request. If every server has an individual pattern of request, \n            consider in-memory caching\n\nLoad Balancers - \n    1. Useful to distribute load evenly to multiple instances of the server (horizontally scaled).\n    2. There are 5 different algorithms - \n    3. Round Robin - \n         a. Load Balancer simply route the request to the next server in a cyclic way. \n         b. All the servers will get equal load.\n         c. What happens if few instances of the server are more powerful than the other ones ? Ideally, powerful ones should get more request than other ones.\n    4. Least Connected -\n         a. The load balancer will maintain a state in its memory to track the transaction/connection allocated to each server instance.\n         b. It will route the transactions/requests to the least connected server.\n         c. If the S1 has reached 8/10 transactions per second and S2 also reach 9/10 transactions per second and S3 has reached 5/10, it will redirect to S3.\n    5. Weighted Round Robin / Weighted Least Connection - \n         a. Each Server will be assigned a weight based on its capability. The weight can be assigned statically or dynamically.\n         b. For dynamic weights, load balancers have to periodically check the health of the servers to understand their system conditions (such as CPU load)\n         c. Each server will assigned a weight percentage W(i)/W(T) where i = instance and T = total.\n         d. The max TPS on each server will be calculated as  [W(i)/W(T) * maxTPS on Load Balancer].\n         e. Example - Powerful server S1 will have weight 5, S2 and S3 will have 2 and 3 respectively. If the max TPS on load balancer is 100, then max TPS of \n                        S1 will be [5/10 * 100] = 50, S2 = [2/10 * 100] = 20 and S3 = [3/10 * 100] = 30.\n         f. The load balancer will maintain a state in its memory to track the transaction/requests allocated to each server instance.\n         g. If the S1 has reach 40/50, which means 0.8 and S2 also reach 10/20, which means 0.5 and S3 has reached 10/30, which means 0.33, \n             it will redirect to S3 as it has the least connections as per its capability.\n   6. IP Hashing -\n         a. Based on the client IP address, the load balancer will [hash(client-ip-address) % 2^32] and then route the request to the server close to the number.\n         b. The server location in the hash ring would be [hash(node-ip-address) % 2^32].\n         c. This is exactly similar to the shardingh concept where we use consistent hashing in a hash ring.\n   7. Least Response Time - \n        a. The load balancer will maintain a state of average response time of all the servers.\n        b. It will find the min of the response time and route the request to that server.\n        c. In doing so, it may happen all the requests are going to that 1 server.\n        d. To prevent it from happening, we can assign a weight to each of the server similar to Weighted round robin concept.\n        e. Instead of finding the minimum of average response time, we will find the minimum of average response time (i) / Weight(i) where i = instance of the server\n           and then route the request.\n\nRate Limiter - (Routing Service --> Rate Limiter --> Message Broker --> Load Balancer --> Micro-service)\n    1. First the request will go to the routing the service to identify the microservice\n    2. Once micro-service identified, we will create a cache with key = service_id and value as <counter> in Redis.\n    3. If the TPS allowed is 50, we will increment the counter till 50 within that second.\n    4. We will remove the cached key after the second (which is TTL)\n    5. If redis successfully increments the counter of the cache key, we proceed to allow-list the request to the correct service.\n    6. If redis fails, we will throttle the traffic using a message broker.\n    7. It can also preserve idempotency in use-cases like fraud-detection (bot clicking multiple times to fool ad aggregation service)\n\n\nMessage Broker (Queue based)\n    1. Producer send messages to the queue and a single consumer retrieves the message from the queue. other consumers don't receive the same message (1:1)\n    2. If there are multiple consumers consuming the same message at the same time, you can use distributed lock to mimic visibility timeout. \n    3. Consumer is responsible for pulling the message and can process at its own speed.\n    4. If we horizontally scale a message broker, we are basically creating more servers under the hood with each server having storage disks\n        and the server with less load should get the incoming request (or it is decided by some load balancing algorithm)\n\n\nMessage Broker (Pub/Sub Based)\n    1. Producer sends a message to a topic/group and all the consumer who are subscribed to the topic receives the message (Fan Out 1:N)\n    2. Consumer just keeps on receiving the message. If it is down, it is lost. (Not poll-based)\n    3. Pub/Sub usually means a message is short-lived, but it also remains in the disk and follows the logical data structure of a queue.\n    4. If we horizontally scale a message broker, we are basically creating more servers under the hood with each server having storage disks\n        and the server with less load should get the incoming request (or it is decided by some load balancing algorithm)\n\n\nMessage Event Stream\n    1. Publisher writes message and partition key. Using consistent hashing, partition key is used to find the right shard. These messages are written in log-based disk file \n        for that shard server.\n    2. All consumers are eligible to receive the message (similar to SNS) or can use poll-based mechanism (Similar to SQS).\n        All consumers keeps track of last message read as message is not deleted after retrieval. \n    3. Since the events are ordered, if we horizontally scale a stream, we have to create more servers of the streams (shards) and apply consistent hashing on partition key \n        so that the messages go to right shard and append to the log-based disk file.\n\nMessage Event Stream Aggregator\n    1. Aggregator reads from event streams and aggregates in memory for a fixed period of window, then outputs to Database. \n        For Durability, aggregator does persist data in disk.\n    2. If event streams are scaled to multiple shards, aggregator can also scale to multiple shards but scaling is less or equal to event streams.\n    3. Aggregator can read data comfortably from streams whose throughput is maxed out. This is because streams throughput involves writing to disks whereas\n        Aggregator reads and store them in memory for aggregation.\n    4. Aggregator persist checkpoint of streaming events in disk (S3). So, in case of crash, it looses its in-memory state, so it starts to read the events from the stream\n        from that particular checkpoint and aggregates in memory.\n\nSearch Optimized Database \n     1. When we add a document to such database, it goes to 1 shard based on partition key (consistent hashing). That shard is responsible for persisting the document\n         in the log-based disk file, in memory, replicate to slave shards, modify the inverted index and return success.\n     2. It is best for read heavy. Relax replication to slave shards to relax consistency is needed.\n     3. It uses Lucene as its underlying search algorithm for a particular shard. When we search the database using a word, every shard lookup for that word in its \n         Lucene's inverted index,  gathers all the data and provide to node for aggregating all results and produce the output.\n    4. Any updates to existing record/document creates a new entry in disk and marks the old one as deleted.\n    5. If you have smaller data set, rely on SQL for full table scan using LIKE command\n\nJob Scheduler\n    1. Schedule jobs via CRON command for every message (Event Bridge)\n       \n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
