zon.com\n   8. So, now when a user in Asia makes a request on API.amazon.com/GET, \n      DNS will receive the request and also fetch client's user location.  \n      Based on geo-based DNS routing protocol (not done dive deep), it will figure out that the request needs \n      to be forwarded to API-asia.amazon.com, which is a server deployed in ASIA and \n      knows about its nearest data center close to Asia. \n   9. For validation, it will check the map in the distributed system to find the respective shard of that user,'\n      which will be its nearest data center.\n   10. What happens if the user in Asia moves to Europe and makes a request on API.amazon.com/GET\n   11. The DNS will receive the request and fetch the user's current location. Based on geo-based DNS routing protocol\n       it will figure out that the request needs to be forwarded to API-europe.amazon.com. \n   12. However, on checking the map in the distributed system, it will find the shard location to be in Asia.\n        So, the europe server will need to forward the request to asia server using the DNS API-asia.amazon.com\n   13. This will also increase the latency to serve the user request. If the europe server sees that the request\n        for the user has increased consistently from Europe, the practical approach would be to create replicas of the shard\n       with shard serving the most write request as the master and others are slave (read)\n   14. Remember, we used server as the external endpoint to our system. Ideally, it would be a routing service (such as AWS API Gateway)\n\n\nCascading Failures in the Servers - \n   1. Say User --> ServerA --> ServerB --> Database. Suddenly, database hits a bottleneck and started serving less requests. As a result, ServerB is \n      affected and started returning more non-200 codes to ServerA which in turns sends non-200 code to the user. This leads to cascade of failures.\n   2. In this case, ServerB should maintain knowledge on the response codes from the server and its average response time. If it sees that the response\n       codes are increasing for non-200 or average response time is exceeding a certain threshold, ServerB should gradually lower its TPS and ultimately be 0.\n   3. At the same time, ServerA should also maintain a knowledge on the response codes from the server and its average response time. If it sees that the response\n      codes are increasing for non-200 (in this case, it would be 429 as requests are getting dropped) or average response time is exceeding a certain threshold, \n      ServerA should gradually lower its TPS and ultimately be 0.\n   4. However, ServerB should not accept any request from ServerA but at the same time keep on pinging the database.\n   5. Now when Database starts returning 200 codes or average response time starts to lower down, ServerB can gradually increase the TPS \n      such that it does not overwhelm the database.\n   6. Similarly, ServerA can also gradually increase the TPS such that it does not overwhelm ServerB.\n\n\nRetries for Server-Client Request -\n    1. We can have different retry strategy to retry a client request - \n    2. Normal Retry - where every client's request is retried after a fixed period of interval. This means if 5 clients makes a request at the same time and it fails,\n       the next retry of all the five clients would be at (T + fixed period)\n    3. Exponential backoff - where every client's request is retried after a exponential period of time. The math = initial delay * (2^N) where N is number of retries.\n       This means if 5 clients makes a request at the same time and it fails, the next retry would be at [1 * 2^0], the next retry would be 2 seconds, 4 seconds and so on.\n    4. Exponential backoff is more preferred as it will give the system more time to recover by exponentially increasing the retry period.\n    5. However, both of the retry strategy does not solve the problem where all of the 5 clients requests are retried at the same time. This is called \n       thundering herd problem.\n    6. Full Jitter with Exponential backoff - To solve this, we can add a bit of randomness to every client request while following the exponential backoff strategy.\n    7. The math for full jitter is random(0, 2^N) where where N is number of retries.\n    8. This means if 5 clients makes a request at the same time and it fails, the next retry would be random(0, 2^0) - so there is a high probability of all the requests getting\n        retried in 1 second. However, this will make more sense if we are retrying for the 4th time, then every client request would be random(0, 2^3) and the probability of \n        all requests being retried at the same time reduces.   \n\nDevice Native Push Notification Service -\n      a. Devices will have to register itself to the service and can disconnect.\n      b. These service will send a notification to the devices even if they are not connected.\n      c. Example - Apple Push Notification Service or Firebase Cloud Messaging",
