      "locked": false,
      "text": "KEY TECHNOLOGIES\n\nAmazon RDS MySQL For Relational Database Selection\n   1. Storage:  64 TiB\n   2. Read/Write IOPS:  3K IOPS/second --> 2 IOPS per read and write (page + query)\n   3. Storage Throughput:   125 MiB/s  \n   4. Compute Throughput:  594 MiB/s \n\nDynamoDB (Read-Heavy Non-Relational Database)\n   1. Primary Key (Partition Key for equality and Sort Key for Range based query) is constant but schema/attributes can differ for every record.\n   2. Partition Key uses HashIndex whereas SortKey uses B+Tree Index.\n   2. Global Secondary Index is different Partition Key but same Sort Key. On the other hand, Local Secondary Index is same partition key but \n       different sort key.\n   3. DynamoDB Streams is used as Capture Database Change (CDC) for streaming events happening in DyanamoDB.\n   4. Cons  - Table-Joins/Complex Queries are expensive as compared to SQL\n   5. Storage:  Unlimited\n   6. Read/Write IOPS:  40K IOPS/second (3K IOPS/sec for every partition = 13 partitions)\n   7. Read Throughput: 156 MiB/s (40K × 4KB) Block Size for READ = 4KB\n   8. Write Throughput:  39 MiB/s (40K × 1KB)  Block Size for WRITE = 1KB\n\nCassandra (Write-Heavy Non-Relational Database)\n   1. Primary Key (Partition Key for equality and Clustering Key for Range based query) is constant but schema/attributes can differ for every record.\n   2. Primary Key uses Log Structured Merge Tree Index for write-heavy operations which makes reads slower.\n   3. Append only \n   3. Cons  - Table-Joins/Complex Queries are expensive as compared to SQL\n   4. Storage - 10TB\n   5. Write IOPS: 45K IOPS/sec and Read IOPS: 30K IOPS/sec\n   6. Read Throughput: 300 MiB/s\n   7. Write Throughput: 300 MiB/s   \n\nRedis - \n    1. It can act as a cache and lock in a distributed system.\n    2. It can act as a message broker such as SQS\n    3. It can act as a event driven pub/sub such as SNS\n    4. It can act as a rate limiter also.\n    5. It supports Inverted Indexes as well as GeoHashIndexes\n    6. Storage - 20GB-1TB\n    7. Read/Write IOPS: 100K IOPS/Sec\n    8. Read/Write Throughput: 1500MiB/sec (only in memory)\n\nAPI Gateways \n    1. Act as a single entry point to route your request to the correct microservice and return the response.\n    2. It support middle-ware such authentication, routing services, load balancer, rate limiting (limiting the request to exceed max TPS), \n        throttling traffic (queue the request if the rate limiting reached its max), etc\n    3. Use it when you have a micro-services architecture and don't use it when you have a simple client-server architecture \n       because routing service will only route the request to the single server.\n\nAmazon SQS (as a Message Broker)\n    1. Message Size: 256KB\n    2. Retention: 14 days\n    3. Standard Queue - No ordering but unlimited throughput. Under the hood, SQS scales indefinitely.\n    4. FIFO Queue - Ordering but 3000 messages/sec for 1 message group. You can have multiple groups in FIFO. \n        Under the hood, SQS scales finitely with every message group (shard based on message group) going to same shard.\n    5. SQS have retry mechanism, post which it goes to DLQ for investigation.\n\nAmazon SNS (as a PubSub)\n    1. Message Size: 256 KB\n    2. Retention: 23 days for retries only. Once consumed, it is deleted.\n    3. Standard Topics: No ordering but unlimited throughput. Under the hood, SNS scales indefinitely.\n    4.  FIFO Queue - Ordering but 3000 messages/sec for 1 topic. You can have multiple topic in FIFO. \n         Under the hood, SNS scales finitely with every message group (shard based on message group) going to same shard.\n    5. SNS retires for 23 days. So, the message needs to be sitting on a disk\n    6. Maximum of 5K subscribers\n\nAmazon Kinesis (Event Stream)\n   1. Message Size: 1MB (Record + Partition Key)\n   2. Retention: 365 days\n   3. Ordered with limited throughput --> 1000 shards max with each shard's write throughput of 1MB/sec and read throughput of 2MB/sec.\n   4. Each shard can have a maximum of 5 subscribers sharing 2M/sec\n   5. IOPS = Total throughput / Message Size of 1 KB = 3K IOPS/sec\n\nAmazon Kinesis Data Analytics (Event Stream Aggregator - Apache Flink)\n   1. RAM: 4GB\n   2. KDA also follows a two-step aggregation policy if there are too many shards to listen to.\n   3. Every shard in KDA listens to max amount of shards and aggregate in its own tumbling window and then provide the results to the top\n       KDA shard whose responsibility is to aggregate from all KDA shards.\n   \n\nElastic Search (Search Optimized Database)\n   1. Storage - 50 GB per shard (Max Shard - 1000)\n   2. Write: 5K docs/sec per shard (No fixed block size)\n   3. Read: 500 queries/sec per shard (No fixed block size)\n\nLambdas (Serverless Function)\n   1. Batch size is 10 for SQS\n   2. Batch size is 10K for Kinesis Streams\n",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "KEY TECHNOLOGIES\n\nAmazon RDS MySQL For Relational Database Selection\n   1. Storage:  64 TiB\n   2. Read/Write IOPS:  3K IOPS/second --> 2 IOPS per read and write (page + query)\n   3. Storage Throughput:   125 MiB/s  \n   4. Compute Throughput:  594 MiB/s \n\nDynamoDB (Read-Heavy Non-Relational Database)\n   1. Primary Key (Partition Key for equality and Sort Key for Range based query) is constant but schema/attributes can differ for every record.\n   2. Partition Key uses HashIndex whereas SortKey uses B+Tree Index.\n   2. Global Secondary Index is different Partition Key but same Sort Key. On the other hand, Local Secondary Index is same partition key but \n       different sort key.\n   3. DynamoDB Streams is used as Capture Database Change (CDC) for streaming events happening in DyanamoDB.\n   4. Cons  - Table-Joins/Complex Queries are expensive as compared to SQL\n   5. Storage:  Unlimited\n   6. Read/Write IOPS:  40K IOPS/second (3K IOPS/sec for every partition = 13 partitions)\n   7. Read Throughput: 156 MiB/s (40K × 4KB) Block Size for READ = 4KB\n   8. Write Throughput:  39 MiB/s (40K × 1KB)  Block Size for WRITE = 1KB\n\nCassandra (Write-Heavy Non-Relational Database)\n   1. Primary Key (Partition Key for equality and Clustering Key for Range based query) is constant but schema/attributes can differ for every record.\n   2. Primary Key uses Log Structured Merge Tree Index for write-heavy operations which makes reads slower.\n   3. Append only \n   3. Cons  - Table-Joins/Complex Queries are expensive as compared to SQL\n   4. Storage - 10TB\n   5. Write IOPS: 45K IOPS/sec and Read IOPS: 30K IOPS/sec\n   6. Read Throughput: 300 MiB/s\n   7. Write Throughput: 300 MiB/s   \n\nRedis - \n    1. It can act as a cache and lock in a distributed system.\n    2. It can act as a message broker such as SQS\n    3. It can act as a event driven pub/sub such as SNS\n    4. It can act as a rate limiter also.\n    5. It supports Inverted Indexes as well as GeoHashIndexes\n    6. Storage - 20GB-1TB\n    7. Read/Write IOPS: 100K IOPS/Sec\n    8. Read/Write Throughput: 1500MiB/sec (only in memory)\n\nAPI Gateways \n    1. Act as a single entry point to route your request to the correct microservice and return the response.\n    2. It support middle-ware such authentication, routing services, load balancer, rate limiting (limiting the request to exceed max TPS), \n        throttling traffic (queue the request if the rate limiting reached its max), etc\n    3. Use it when you have a micro-services architecture and don't use it when you have a simple client-server architecture \n       because routing service will only route the request to the single server.\n\nAmazon SQS (as a Message Broker)\n    1. Message Size: 256KB\n    2. Retention: 14 days\n    3. Standard Queue - No ordering but unlimited throughput. Under the hood, SQS scales indefinitely.\n    4. FIFO Queue - Ordering but 3000 messages/sec for 1 message group. You can have multiple groups in FIFO. \n        Under the hood, SQS scales finitely with every message group (shard based on message group) going to same shard.\n    5. SQS have retry mechanism, post which it goes to DLQ for investigation.\n\nAmazon SNS (as a PubSub)\n    1. Message Size: 256 KB\n    2. Retention: 23 days for retries only. Once consumed, it is deleted.\n    3. Standard Topics: No ordering but unlimited throughput. Under the hood, SNS scales indefinitely.\n    4.  FIFO Queue - Ordering but 3000 messages/sec for 1 topic. You can have multiple topic in FIFO. \n         Under the hood, SNS scales finitely with every message group (shard based on message group) going to same shard.\n    5. SNS retires for 23 days. So, the message needs to be sitting on a disk\n    6. Maximum of 5K subscribers\n\nAmazon Kinesis (Event Stream)\n   1. Message Size: 1MB (Record + Partition Key)\n   2. Retention: 365 days\n   3. Ordered with limited throughput --> 1000 shards max with each shard's write throughput of 1MB/sec and read throughput of 2MB/sec.\n   4. Each shard can have a maximum of 5 subscribers sharing 2M/sec\n   5. IOPS = Total throughput / Message Size of 1 KB = 3K IOPS/sec\n\nAmazon Kinesis Data Analytics (Event Stream Aggregator - Apache Flink)\n   1. RAM: 4GB\n   2. KDA also follows a two-step aggregation policy if there are too many shards to listen to.\n   3. Every shard in KDA listens to max amount of shards and aggregate in its own tumbling window and then provide the results to the top\n       KDA shard whose responsibility is to aggregate from all KDA shards.\n   \n\nElastic Search (Search Optimized Database)\n   1. Storage - 50 GB per shard (Max Shard - 1000)\n   2. Write: 5K docs/sec per shard (No fixed block size)\n   3. Read: 500 queries/sec per shard (No fixed block size)\n\nLambdas (Serverless Function)\n   1. Batch size is 10 for SQS\n   2. Batch size is 10K for Kinesis Streams\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "unDV1BHWjcycGgfooVbxT",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 10943.036095930007,
      "y": 7376.54799798304,
      "width": 2906.466552734375,
      "height": 4455,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2Q",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2106021960,
      "version": 16653,
      "versionNonce": 99950217,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1766886772956,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "COMMON PATTERN\n\nSCALING WRITES -\n\nScaling Writes for higher write throughput (more requests coming in - higher TPS)\n   1. Start with sharding the database with partition key which is unique.\n   2. [BATCH REQUESTS] If sharding them does not reduce the load to your expectations and LATENCY is not SENSITIVE\n          a. You can add them to message queues and process at your own speed and hit database at your comfort.\n          b. Aggregate multiple requests and hit database at a specific fixed interval (In-memory aggregation such as Event Processor)\n   3. If the write throughput is higher on a specific shard (Popular Ad), you can be further sharded into multiple instances by using -\n          a. Use compound keys as partition keys - user_id + <timestamp>\n          b. Add randomness to partition keys - user_id + random(0,10) to be distributes to multiple shards.\n    4. If the writes to the database keep on increasing, make a trade-off between rate-limiting or process them later (not latency sensitive).\n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where clients don't affect each other with high writes + high reads(Ad Click Analytics/ Monitoring System) \n    1. We can horizontally scale the service to increase the throughput which would involve making multiple database calls.\n    2. Bad because writing to DB for 1M clicks/ad can lead to max throughput and DB will stop responding and hence clicks will be lost.\n    3. Our requirement should be very simple - \n           a. Avoid hitting database for every click count and perform aggregation in memory.\n           b. For aggregation in memory, you need clicks for a single ad to be in same shard/server so that the aggregator can calculate \n               the count for that window and does not have to care about reading data from other shards.\n    4. We have multiple options - \n          a. SNS + SQS + Lambda + Database - If we take the FIFO approach, the throughput is 3K messages/sec. Even though we have 1 SNS + 1 SQS\n              for a single AD, clients will have operational burden to maintain this pair for every AD. Additionally, if 1 AD becomes hot (say 1M click/sec for a single ad)\n              you are gone.\n          b. DynamoDB Streams - You have to involve DynamoDB which will itself not able to handle 1M clicks/ad throughput which is roughly around\n              1 GB/sec (1 click = 1KB, hence 1M/sec * 1KB = 1GB/sec) \n          c. Kinesis + KDA - Kinesis have a max throughput of 1 GB/sec (1000 shards) which just matches the 1M clicks/sec. Here we need to make sure that partition key is ad_id\n              such that every click count for that ad goes into the same shard. Each KDA shard can listen to Kinesis stream shard which will have complete click count for the ads \n              in that Kinesis shards and it will aggregate them in memory for a fixed window and output to database.\n     5. How will we aggregate data for 1 day, 1 month or 1 year ?\n            a. We can have KDA output aggregations over a period of 1 hour to the database.\n            b. Post that, we can run cron job or aggregate when requested for a certain period.\n     6. What happens if the shard becomes hot due to popular user ? \n            a. If we are reading AD22, we can think of replicas or copying the same AD22 data in multiple shards (same data in different database servers)\n            b. If we are calculating the click count on AD22, hitting that 1 shard would be disaster. Hence, we can divide them into more shards by - \n                a. Compound keys as partition keys - 'Ad_id + timestamp' so that ('AD22 + 10PM')%2 = shard 5 is now getting hit to calculate click count.\n                b. Randomness in Partition keys - 'Ad_id + random(0, 10)' so that this ad can go to any of the shards.\n     7. What happens if you need Aggregation between ads ? (TopK Ads)\n           a. We can have CRON jobs calculating TopK periodically after Kinesis+KDA writes to the database. (OR)\n           b. Have 2 layer streaming architecture where 1st layer of Kinesis + KDA can aggregate per ad and then provide the hourly or monthly data from 1st KDA layer (all shards)\n               to just 1 shard of the 2nd KDA layer which will calculate the TopK and persist it. Similarly, we can do for monthly or daily.\n     8. For high reads during this pattern, focus on pre-computing the data as much as possible. If pre-computing fails, then compute at that instant (But call it out to interviewers)\n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Eventual Consistency + No-Conflict (Whatsapp/LiveComments)\n    1.  In LiveComments and Whatsapp GroupChats, all the instances are publisher and subscriber so that 1 message is broadcasted to all\n         other users in real time.\n    2. Use Pub/Sub mechanism - Select a nice topic and reason about publisher/subscriber. In Direct message, \n         the receiver is the subscriber and sender is the publisher.\n    3. Remember Pub/Sub does not persist message, so there is data loss. IF data loss is a requirement, think of fallback ways (inbox in whatsapp)\n    4. For high writes, focus on the above strategy of using a streaming layer.\n    5. Since users and servers both send message to each other, focus on bi-directional communication (web socket).\n\nHigh-frequency real time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Eventual Consistency + Conflict (Quip docs) -\n    1. Follow the protocol of upload and then download to resolve conflicts\n    2. Clients and server maintain data separately and server owns the responsibility of resolving the conflicts - \n           a.  Client 1 and Client 2 uploads its data to the server which routes it to Conflict Resolution Server\n           b. The server will compare the timestamp and resolve the conflict of making Client 1's chunk as the official copy.\n           c. Once the server publishes the message to Pub/Sub, it is broadcasted to all instances and the instances sends the information to clients.\n           d. Client 1 will compare and find the data's lastUpdatedTimestamp in its local DB is equal to that of server copy and won't do anything.\n           3. Client 2 will compare and find the chunk's lastUpdatedTimestamp in its local DB is less than that of server copy and will download the chunk.\n\nHigh-frequency real time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Strong Consistency  + Conflict (AuctionBidding) -\n    1. For high writes with strong consistency,use distributed lock to only have 1 winner request over other requests made at the same time.\n    2. Follow the principle of using Pub/Sub and broadcast to other server instances for the winning request.\n\n\nSCALING READS\n\nScaling Reads for higher read throughput (more requests coming in - higher TPS)\n    1. Replicas are useful for scaling reads as well as fault-tolerance in database.\n          1. Master replica will accept write/read and slave replicas only accepts reads. \n          2. If a new data gets written to master and services require strong consistency, then all replicas needs to be updated.\n                 a. If we require partial consistency, we can think of quorum in replicas (3/5 replica needs to be updated)\n                 b. If stale data is okay to accept, the read from any replica.\n                 c. If all replica is not updated or we didn't receive a quorum, direct the reads to master till replication is complete\n .  2. Imagine there is 100K requests per second and there is a cache miss, all 100K will hit database with the hot row (Thundering herd). In such cases, \n          a. Combine similar requests into a single request and then hit the database to retrieve the entry. For a hot entry, this is particularly useful. \n          b. In-case the latency is not sensitive, for all the thundering herd requests, you can add jitter/randomness to spread them and avoid hitting database at the same time,\n   3. In case of hot or viral entry (celebrity problems),\n          a. As mentioned above, you can combine multiple requests into a single request and hit the database. \n          b. In case you cannot combine them into a single request, you can persist the hot entry in a cache if spawning more replicas are challenging. Additionally to prevent the entry \n              from being deleted from cache, we can proactively keep updating the TTL or even create a new entry (cache versioning) if the entry gets modified.\n\nScaling Reads for latency sensitive \n    1. Pre-compute the list of data in a cache so that when users request, you don't have to compute a complex query in a database and instead retrieve pre-computed data \n        from cache. These are very helpful for cases such as Feed Generation.\n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where clients only reads and does not affect other clients \n    1. Always use Pub/Sub mechanism if you only want recent data (StockUpdate)\n         a. Only 1 publisher but multiple subscribers\n         b. All of the server will maintain SSE connection.\n    2. Pre-computed cache if you want list of data (PostFeed / NewsFeed/ PriceHistory)\n         a. As you paginate, keep on hitting the database, proactively sensed and initiated by the apps.\n         b. Simple HTTP request should suffice.\n\n\n     \n     ",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "COMMON PATTERN\n\nSCALING WRITES -\n\nScaling Writes for higher write throughput (more requests coming in - higher TPS)\n   1. Start with sharding the database with partition key which is unique.\n   2. [BATCH REQUESTS] If sharding them does not reduce the load to your expectations and LATENCY is not SENSITIVE\n          a. You can add them to message queues and process at your own speed and hit database at your comfort.\n          b. Aggregate multiple requests and hit database at a specific fixed interval (In-memory aggregation such as Event Processor)\n   3. If the write throughput is higher on a specific shard (Popular Ad), you can be further sharded into multiple instances by using -\n          a. Use compound keys as partition keys - user_id + <timestamp>\n          b. Add randomness to partition keys - user_id + random(0,10) to be distributes to multiple shards.\n    4. If the writes to the database keep on increasing, make a trade-off between rate-limiting or process them later (not latency sensitive).\n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where clients don't affect each other with high writes + high reads(Ad Click Analytics/ Monitoring System) \n    1. We can horizontally scale the service to increase the throughput which would involve making multiple database calls.\n    2. Bad because writing to DB for 1M clicks/ad can lead to max throughput and DB will stop responding and hence clicks will be lost.\n    3. Our requirement should be very simple - \n           a. Avoid hitting database for every click count and perform aggregation in memory.\n           b. For aggregation in memory, you need clicks for a single ad to be in same shard/server so that the aggregator can calculate \n               the count for that window and does not have to care about reading data from other shards.\n    4. We have multiple options - \n          a. SNS + SQS + Lambda + Database - If we take the FIFO approach, the throughput is 3K messages/sec. Even though we have 1 SNS + 1 SQS\n              for a single AD, clients will have operational burden to maintain this pair for every AD. Additionally, if 1 AD becomes hot (say 1M click/sec for a single ad)\n              you are gone.\n          b. DynamoDB Streams - You have to involve DynamoDB which will itself not able to handle 1M clicks/ad throughput which is roughly around\n              1 GB/sec (1 click = 1KB, hence 1M/sec * 1KB = 1GB/sec) \n          c. Kinesis + KDA - Kinesis have a max throughput of 1 GB/sec (1000 shards) which just matches the 1M clicks/sec. Here we need to make sure that partition key is ad_id\n              such that every click count for that ad goes into the same shard. Each KDA shard can listen to Kinesis stream shard which will have complete click count for the ads \n              in that Kinesis shards and it will aggregate them in memory for a fixed window and output to database.\n     5. How will we aggregate data for 1 day, 1 month or 1 year ?\n            a. We can have KDA output aggregations over a period of 1 hour to the database.\n            b. Post that, we can run cron job or aggregate when requested for a certain period.\n     6. What happens if the shard becomes hot due to popular user ? \n            a. If we are reading AD22, we can think of replicas or copying the same AD22 data in multiple shards (same data in different database servers)\n            b. If we are calculating the click count on AD22, hitting that 1 shard would be disaster. Hence, we can divide them into more shards by - \n                a. Compound keys as partition keys - 'Ad_id + timestamp' so that ('AD22 + 10PM')%2 = shard 5 is now getting hit to calculate click count.\n                b. Randomness in Partition keys - 'Ad_id + random(0, 10)' so that this ad can go to any of the shards.\n     7. What happens if you need Aggregation between ads ? (TopK Ads)\n           a. We can have CRON jobs calculating TopK periodically after Kinesis+KDA writes to the database. (OR)\n           b. Have 2 layer streaming architecture where 1st layer of Kinesis + KDA can aggregate per ad and then provide the hourly or monthly data from 1st KDA layer (all shards)\n               to just 1 shard of the 2nd KDA layer which will calculate the TopK and persist it. Similarly, we can do for monthly or daily.\n     8. For high reads during this pattern, focus on pre-computing the data as much as possible. If pre-computing fails, then compute at that instant (But call it out to interviewers)\n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Eventual Consistency + No-Conflict (Whatsapp/LiveComments)\n    1.  In LiveComments and Whatsapp GroupChats, all the instances are publisher and subscriber so that 1 message is broadcasted to all\n         other users in real time.\n    2. Use Pub/Sub mechanism - Select a nice topic and reason about publisher/subscriber. In Direct message, \n         the receiver is the subscriber and sender is the publisher.\n    3. Remember Pub/Sub does not persist message, so there is data loss. IF data loss is a requirement, think of fallback ways (inbox in whatsapp)\n    4. For high writes, focus on the above strategy of using a streaming layer.\n    5. Since users and servers both send message to each other, focus on bi-directional communication (web socket).\n\nHigh-frequency real time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Eventual Consistency + Conflict (Quip docs) -\n    1. Follow the protocol of upload and then download to resolve conflicts\n    2. Clients and server maintain data separately and server owns the responsibility of resolving the conflicts - \n           a.  Client 1 and Client 2 uploads its data to the server which routes it to Conflict Resolution Server\n           b. The server will compare the timestamp and resolve the conflict of making Client 1's chunk as the official copy.\n           c. Once the server publishes the message to Pub/Sub, it is broadcasted to all instances and the instances sends the information to clients.\n           d. Client 1 will compare and find the data's lastUpdatedTimestamp in its local DB is equal to that of server copy and won't do anything.\n           3. Client 2 will compare and find the chunk's lastUpdatedTimestamp in its local DB is less than that of server copy and will download the chunk.\n\nHigh-frequency real time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Strong Consistency  + Conflict (AuctionBidding) -\n    1. For high writes with strong consistency,use distributed lock to only have 1 winner request over other requests made at the same time.\n    2. Follow the principle of using Pub/Sub and broadcast to other server instances for the winning request.\n\n\nSCALING READS\n\nScaling Reads for higher read throughput (more requests coming in - higher TPS)\n    1. Replicas are useful for scaling reads as well as fault-tolerance in database.\n          1. Master replica will accept write/read and slave replicas only accepts reads. \n          2. If a new data gets written to master and services require strong consistency, then all replicas needs to be updated.\n                 a. If we require partial consistency, we can think of quorum in replicas (3/5 replica needs to be updated)\n                 b. If stale data is okay to accept, the read from any replica.\n                 c. If all replica is not updated or we didn't receive a quorum, direct the reads to master till replication is complete\n .  2. Imagine there is 100K requests per second and there is a cache miss, all 100K will hit database with the hot row (Thundering herd). In such cases, \n          a. Combine similar requests into a single request and then hit the database to retrieve the entry. For a hot entry, this is particularly useful. \n          b. In-case the latency is not sensitive, for all the thundering herd requests, you can add jitter/randomness to spread them and avoid hitting database at the same time,\n   3. In case of hot or viral entry (celebrity problems),\n          a. As mentioned above, you can combine multiple requests into a single request and hit the database. \n          b. In case you cannot combine them into a single request, you can persist the hot entry in a cache if spawning more replicas are challenging. Additionally to prevent the entry \n              from being deleted from cache, we can proactively keep updating the TTL or even create a new entry (cache versioning) if the entry gets modified.\n\nScaling Reads for latency sensitive \n    1. Pre-compute the list of data in a cache so that when users request, you don't have to compute a complex query in a database and instead retrieve pre-computed data \n        from cache. These are very helpful for cases such as Feed Generation.\n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where clients only reads and does not affect other clients \n    1. Always use Pub/Sub mechanism if you only want recent data (StockUpdate)\n         a. Only 1 publisher but multiple subscribers\n         b. All of the server will maintain SSE connection.\n    2. Pre-computed cache if you want list of data (PostFeed / NewsFeed/ PriceHistory)\n         a. As you paginate, keep on hitting the database, proactively sensed and initiated by the apps.\n         b. Simple HTTP request should suffice.\n\n\n     \n     ",
