 is backend server which uses S3 as cloud storage.\n    2. When I want to upload a photo, the app (client) will make a request to backend server which will return a pre-signed URL and save metadata\n        information in the database.\n    3. The app will directly upload the attachment to S3, where S3 will validate the pre-signed URL.\n    4. When I want to view the photo in my app, the app will send a request to server which will return the Content Deliver Network URL (AWS Cloud Front)\n        to the app.\n    5. The app will proceed to connect with CDN to fetch the photo. If the CDN does not have the image in the cache, it will retrieve the pre-signed URL\n         from the CDN URL and make a call to S3 to download the image, cache it and then return it to the app.\n        \n\nUploading a large file (>10MB) with resume-able upload/download \n    1. Amazon Photos app needs to upload a 5GB file. The app takes the responsibility of splitting the large file using SPLIT command into smaller chunks say 5MB. \n        You can also use AWS Client SDK which will take care of stripping as well as generating a unique fingerprint for every chunk\n    2. The app will persist all of these chunks metadata in its local DB and make a request to server to upload this large file by providing all the chunk metadata.\n    3. The server will persist all the chunk metadata to the file-id in its DB and would provide pre-signed URL for all the chunks to the app.\n    4. The app will start uploading the chunk to S3 and on completion will update its local and SERVER DB accordingly with progress metadata and timestamp\n        to avoid single point of failure if device crashes\n    5. If the network connection breaks, the app knows till what chunk it uploaded and S3 will have partial data.\n    6. Once the network resumes, the app will start uploading the remaining chunk to S3. Once it completes, it sends a request to server with updated chunk\n        metadata and the server sends a completion request to S3 stating that upload is complete. Post that S3 internally consolidates the chunk to make it a big file.\n            a. To guarantee correctness, the server and S3 can have a notification queue which says that a chunk has been uploaded and the server should update the \n                metadata in its backend. In this way, the app need not send all the progress metadata of the all the chunks at Step 6. \n                The app can only send that it is done, so that the server can say the same to S3. \n    7. Now, we need to download the photo. The app makes a request to server which provides with CDN URL (it has pre-signed S3 URL)\n    8. The app keeps a track of what portion of the file has been download. CDN and S3 does not know what part of the data has been downloaded.\n    9. If the network breaks and resumes, the app needs to specify the range to be downloaded from CDN.\n          a. GET /large-file.zip\n              Range: bytes=0-10485759  (first 10MB)\n   10. If the local and server has FileCHUNKMETADATA table for every file, we can proceed with delta sync where we can identify which CHUNKS are NEW and which got\n          DELETED, so that only those can be updated across devices.\n\nMulti-Step Workflow (E-commerce)\n      1. All Orders looks like a finite state machine (Order Placed - Inventory Update - Payment - Confirmation)\n      2. All the state transitions for each order needs to be persisted in the event of crash\n      3. There could be multiple instances of the workers working for same state to transition an order to that state to new state. For example, multiple instances of the payment workers\n           will pick up the orders sitting in Payment state, talk to payment service, if succeeded, transition to confirmation state, where confirmation workers will confirm to the user\n          Else failed state where failure workers send a rejection email to users.\n\n\nLong Running Tasks (Trans-coding for youtube video)\n     1. For tasks which require a lot of computational power and is a long running process, the server should put the task in a queue, update its database \n         and reply back to the client that is is ongoing.\n     2. A lambda worker (from multiple instances) will read from the queue, execute the task and update the server's database.\n     3. The server database can then notify the server that task has been completed, to which server can respond to the client. \n     4. The server-client communication could SSE or web-socket.\n     5. Since we have bunch of lambda workers (stateless), we ideally should maintain a heartbeat mechanism so that we can spawn a new one but AWS handles auto-scaling.\n     6. You can also separate queues based on approximate task type (Generating a report takes 5 seconds where transcoding may take 1 hour)\n     7. For these 1 hour tasks, we may need to implement the multi-step-workflow - prefer server to own the responsibility of finite state machine for that job\n         and break the job into smaller parts for easy and shorter processing.",
