    {
      "id": "Ev9tGl2U2uLe_O77dx3JB",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 488.40336066891746,
      "y": -1137.5399581926347,
      "width": 1782.300048828125,
      "height": 3873.6214811304776,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2W",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 973784039,
      "version": 11985,
      "versionNonce": 2109393959,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1766893785660,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Strava (Fitness App)\n\nFunctional Requirements - \n   1. Users should be able to start, pause, stop, and save their runs and rides.\n   2. While running or cycling, users should be able to view that activity's data, including route, distance, and time.\n   3. Users should be able to view details about their own completed activities as well as the activities of their friends.\n\nNon-Functional Requirements - \n    a. The latency to start, pause, stop and saving their ride should be in real time (< 100ms)\n    b. View the current ride data should be instantaneous\n    c. Viewing details about their or friend's activities should be in real time (< 100ms)\n    d. The system should prioritize availability in the use-case of viewing friend's activity.\n    e. The system should prioritize strong consistency in the use-case of viewing own activity or making some operations\n         in the current activity.\n    f. The system should not be prone to data loss and should not have a single point of failure.\n    g. Considering 10M concurrent activities, the system should decide the frequency of interaction. In such cases, we can \n        add some wiggle room to update activity data (such a route, distance and time) upto a minute. However, CRUD\n        operations like Start, Stop, Pause, Save should be instant.\n    h. The system should have offline capability to cache data locally and sync later\n\n\nCore Entities - \n    1. Activity\n    2. Users (Including Friends)\n\nAPI Contracts - \n\n1. Users should be able to start, pause, stop, and save their runs and rides.\n \nPOST /activity/ --> Start a ride and return with activityId and status code 200\n{\n    userId\n    timestamp\n    ..metadata\n}\n\nPATCH /activity/<activityId> --> Pause, Stop and Save their rides and return with confirmationID and status code 200\n{\n     userId\n     Operation: Pause|Stop|Completed\n     timestamp\n     ...metadata\n}\n\n2. users should be able to view that activity's data, including route, distance, and time.\n\nGET /activity/<activityId>\n{\n     userId\n     currentStatus: Pause|Stop|Completed\n     TotalDistanceCovered\n     TotalTimeTaken\n     RouteCovered: List<Lat,Long>\n     LastModifiedtimestamp\n     CreationTimestamp\n}\n\n3. Users should be able to view their activities as well as friend's activity\n\nGET /activity/<userId>\n{\n    Name\n    DaysSinceJoining\n    ConsistencyStatistics\n    TotalActivitiesCompleted\n    TotalActivitiesPaused\n    Activities: List<Activity>\n}\n\nHigh Level Design \n\n1. Users should be able to start, pause, stop, and save their runs and rides.\n     a. The App makes a POST/PATCH request to the 'Sync' microservice which makes a DB call to insert/update a record in the ACTIVITY table.\n     b. If the App needs to make further requests to pause, stop and save their rides, they need to make another call to the same microservice\n         which will update the ACTIVITY table.\n\n2. While running or cycling, users should be able to view that activity's data, including route, distance, and time.\n      a. The App should be solely responsible for showing live statistics about route location, distance covered and time taken.\n      b. In such cases, the app should have a local DB containing the same fields as in the Server Database.\n      c. Since the local DB is for per user, we don't need userId as column. However, we need to sync local DB with the server DB within a minute (as per our requirements)\n      d. The GPS in the phone should be main data source which would provide data to the App for local Persistence, which would work in offline scenarios.\n      e. The data from the GPS will consist lat, long which should be persisted in the RouteCovered. \n      f. For time taken, we can calculate the LastModifiedTimestamp - CreationTimestamp.\n\n3. Users should be able to view details about their own completed activities as well as the activities of their friends.\n     a. The App will make a GET request to the 'Stats' microservice to fetch their own activity. The microservice will query the ACTIVITY table to fetch the list of all activities\n         done by the user.\n     b. If the user wants to see all his friend's activity, the microservice would query FOLLOW table to get the list of userId that the current user follows and then query\n         ACTIVITY table to fetch the list of Top 50 activities sorted by LastModifiedTimestamp\n     c. We would require Pagination for the current user to effectively paginate through all the friend's or own activities\n\n4. For a long bike ride in particular, recalculating the total distance based on the route can get expensive. How can you make this more efficient?\n      a. Total Distance at any point in time covered is the current GPS Lat/Long - Previous Lat/Long. We can keep the previous Distance calculated and previous Lat/Long noted in memory and then\n          when we receive new Lat/Long, we can use Total Distance = PreviousDistance + (New Lat,Long - Last Lat, Long)\n      b. However, we need not be precise as the users had no way of validating. Instead of calculating the distance every second, we can have a wiggle room of like 30 seconds.\n      c. Say if a user's speed is 5m/sec and after 30 seconds, the user covers 150m, we can update the live statistics. Remember, this kind of decision depends upon UI.\n      d. if the UI has distance with precision of 2 decimal points, trigger GPS every 30 seconds is efficient. However, if the precision is 10 decimal points, we may have to trigger GPS every sec.\n          \n\n 5. When calculating the distance between consecutive GPS points using the incremental approach you described, how would you handle scenarios where GPS accuracy varies significantly, \n       such as when the user goes through a tunnel or under heavy tree cover, potentially causing erratic jumps in location data?\n         a. In case of scenarios where we are unable to get GPS data, the system should initially capture the user's speed. \n         b. Say if user's average speed is 5m/sec and after 30 seconds, we want to trigger GPS query and does not get the result, we would simply do TotalDistance = PreviousDistance + (Speed * Time)\n             which would add 150 metrics (for this scenario) to the last total distance.\n         c. If we were able to get the GPS data, we would proceed with previous calculation of Total Distance = PreviousDistance + (New Lat,Long - Last Lat, Long)\n\n6. How will your system support tracking activities while the users device is offline? \n       a. In case of offline scenarios, App1 should own the responsibility of maintaining the list of non-synced activities in its local DB.\n       b. So, when a user requests for Start/Stop/Pause an activity, local DB should persist that information.\n       c. If the user wants to start a new activity, local DB should also persist that information\n       d. If the App crashes and restarts, the data can be fetched from the local DB in the device. \n       e. So, as soon as the device is online and LastSyncedTimestamp < LastModifiedTimestamp, trigger a sync via the 'Sync' microservice.\n       f. The microservice would be responsible to persist the information in the Server DB.\n\n7. When the device comes back online after an extended offline period, how would you handle the case where the user has modified the same activity on multiple devices, \n      or where the local activity data conflicts with what's already on the server?\n      a. This is a scenario of multiple conflicts and we need a service to resolve conflicts.\n      b. Say a user is operating on multiple devices and both of them is offline. When they come online, the respective apps would sent a request to Sync microservice \n          where each request's LastModifedTimestamp would be different from others. In such scenarios, the microservice should own the responsibility of checking\n          which request's LastModifiedTimestamp is latest and process the single request. For the one that failed, reply back to the App saying something went wrong, please refresh.\n      c. However, if these 2 requests are not fired at the same time, the one which reaches the Sync Microservice first will simply modify the Activity Table.\n      d. Now, when the second request is fired, the Sync Microservice checks if the LastModifiedTimestamp (Of server) == LastSyncedTimestamp (Of localDB) is same. If it is not,\n          that means App2 localDB is not synced and user has added actions on top of them. Ask App2 to resync and then add actions on top of them.\n\n8. How can we support up-to-date sharing of activities with friends while the activity is in progress, not just after completion?\n      a. This seems to be fan-out problem where we want to share the current active activity. In such scenarios, both users and their friends should be connected to the App.\n      b. When the user's app's localDB wants to sync, it will send a request to the Sync microservice. The microservice should own the major responsibility of persisting that \n           information to the DB and then proceed to publish 'RouteLocation', 'DistanceCovered', 'TimeTaken' to Pub/Sub.\n      c. Here, we can have a logic of creating a topic when the user clicks on 'Share Live Stats' button and the Sync Microservice will have the responsibility of publishing to the Pub/Sub.\n      d. Now, friends sitting in App2 or App3 will get a notification to accept the user's live sharing activity. Once accepted, their Sync microservice instances will subscribe to that topic\n          and will not start receiving messages which would be returned by Sync Microservice to App2 and App3.\n      e. All of this connection between App and Sync are bi-directional, hence we would proceed with WebSocket Connection.\n\nAnother approach - Their friends can also periodically poll at a fixed interval to get their friend's data by using GET activity/<UserID>\n     a. Having too many websocket connections would put a lot of load on the CPU resources.\n     b. If live is not instantaneous and we are okay with some amount of delay, we would like to proceed with fixed polling as it is a simple HTTP request \n         and will query the database and would provide the data in real time. It will also help in getting rid of Pub/sub mechanism.\n     c. If the user is a celebrity, we can persist the activity information to a cache with TTL of N + 10 seconds. So, that when a new update comes, \n          we can write to cache again so that other friends/followers can query the cache to reduce the load on database.\n\n9. How can we expose an up-to-date leaderboard of top athletes globally based on the total distance covered?\n     a. When you mention Top athletes, it should be a finite number.\n     b. Since this is a leaderboard, it would be heavily queries and need to sustain a heavy read throughput and near real time latency.\n     c. To satisfy both the constraints, we can have a running cache with Sorted Set based on total Distance Covered.\n     d. To write to the cache, anytime a Sync micoservice updates the DB, it can have a stream which would flow into the cache and update the Sorted Set.\n     d. When an App requests to view the leaderboard, the Stats microservice would read from the cache and return the Top 50-100 athletes.\n\n10. In your Redis Sorted Set approach, how would you handle the scenario where a user retroactively edits a completed activity to correct the distance, and this update needs \n       to be reflected in the global leaderboard? Walk me through the flow from the edit request to the cache update.\n         a. App1 makes a PATCH request to Sync1 service to sync the local DB to the ServerDB, The microservice updates the Activity with the parameters sent. \n         b. The DB recognizes a UPDATE call and trigger a stream (similar to DynamoDB stream - event stream). \n         c. The consumer of the stream could be a serverless Lambda which processes 1 message/sec and call ADD SORTEDSET.\n         d. The SortedSet has an underlying data structure of Red Black Tree which rebalances itself on every insert. Since the set is bounded, the one activity which exceeds the \n              the sorted set size is eliminated.\n",
      "fontSize": 19.99288506389924,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Strava (Fitness App)\n\nFunctional Requirements - \n   1. Users should be able to start, pause, stop, and save their runs and rides.\n   2. While running or cycling, users should be able to view that activity's data, including route, distance, and time.\n   3. Users should be able to view details about their own completed activities as well as the activities of their friends.\n\nNon-Functional Requirements - \n    a. The latency to start, pause, stop and saving their ride should be in real time (< 100ms)\n    b. View the current ride data should be instantaneous\n    c. Viewing details about their or friend's activities should be in real time (< 100ms)\n    d. The system should prioritize availability in the use-case of viewing friend's activity.\n    e. The system should prioritize strong consistency in the use-case of viewing own activity or making some operations\n         in the current activity.\n    f. The system should not be prone to data loss and should not have a single point of failure.\n    g. Considering 10M concurrent activities, the system should decide the frequency of interaction. In such cases, we can \n        add some wiggle room to update activity data (such a route, distance and time) upto a minute. However, CRUD\n        operations like Start, Stop, Pause, Save should be instant.\n    h. The system should have offline capability to cache data locally and sync later\n\n\nCore Entities - \n    1. Activity\n    2. Users (Including Friends)\n\nAPI Contracts - \n\n1. Users should be able to start, pause, stop, and save their runs and rides.\n \nPOST /activity/ --> Start a ride and return with activityId and status code 200\n{\n    userId\n    timestamp\n    ..metadata\n}\n\nPATCH /activity/<activityId> --> Pause, Stop and Save their rides and return with confirmationID and status code 200\n{\n     userId\n     Operation: Pause|Stop|Completed\n     timestamp\n     ...metadata\n}\n\n2. users should be able to view that activity's data, including route, distance, and time.\n\nGET /activity/<activityId>\n{\n     userId\n     currentStatus: Pause|Stop|Completed\n     TotalDistanceCovered\n     TotalTimeTaken\n     RouteCovered: List<Lat,Long>\n     LastModifiedtimestamp\n     CreationTimestamp\n}\n\n3. Users should be able to view their activities as well as friend's activity\n\nGET /activity/<userId>\n{\n    Name\n    DaysSinceJoining\n    ConsistencyStatistics\n    TotalActivitiesCompleted\n    TotalActivitiesPaused\n    Activities: List<Activity>\n}\n\nHigh Level Design \n\n1. Users should be able to start, pause, stop, and save their runs and rides.\n     a. The App makes a POST/PATCH request to the 'Sync' microservice which makes a DB call to insert/update a record in the ACTIVITY table.\n     b. If the App needs to make further requests to pause, stop and save their rides, they need to make another call to the same microservice\n         which will update the ACTIVITY table.\n\n2. While running or cycling, users should be able to view that activity's data, including route, distance, and time.\n      a. The App should be solely responsible for showing live statistics about route location, distance covered and time taken.\n      b. In such cases, the app should have a local DB containing the same fields as in the Server Database.\n      c. Since the local DB is for per user, we don't need userId as column. However, we need to sync local DB with the server DB within a minute (as per our requirements)\n      d. The GPS in the phone should be main data source which would provide data to the App for local Persistence, which would work in offline scenarios.\n      e. The data from the GPS will consist lat, long which should be persisted in the RouteCovered. \n      f. For time taken, we can calculate the LastModifiedTimestamp - CreationTimestamp.\n\n3. Users should be able to view details about their own completed activities as well as the activities of their friends.\n     a. The App will make a GET request to the 'Stats' microservice to fetch their own activity. The microservice will query the ACTIVITY table to fetch the list of all activities\n         done by the user.\n     b. If the user wants to see all his friend's activity, the microservice would query FOLLOW table to get the list of userId that the current user follows and then query\n         ACTIVITY table to fetch the list of Top 50 activities sorted by LastModifiedTimestamp\n     c. We would require Pagination for the current user to effectively paginate through all the friend's or own activities\n\n4. For a long bike ride in particular, recalculating the total distance based on the route can get expensive. How can you make this more efficient?\n      a. Total Distance at any point in time covered is the current GPS Lat/Long - Previous Lat/Long. We can keep the previous Distance calculated and previous Lat/Long noted in memory and then\n          when we receive new Lat/Long, we can use Total Distance = PreviousDistance + (New Lat,Long - Last Lat, Long)\n      b. However, we need not be precise as the users had no way of validating. Instead of calculating the distance every second, we can have a wiggle room of like 30 seconds.\n      c. Say if a user's speed is 5m/sec and after 30 seconds, the user covers 150m, we can update the live statistics. Remember, this kind of decision depends upon UI.\n      d. if the UI has distance with precision of 2 decimal points, trigger GPS every 30 seconds is efficient. However, if the precision is 10 decimal points, we may have to trigger GPS every sec.\n          \n\n 5. When calculating the distance between consecutive GPS points using the incremental approach you described, how would you handle scenarios where GPS accuracy varies significantly, \n       such as when the user goes through a tunnel or under heavy tree cover, potentially causing erratic jumps in location data?\n         a. In case of scenarios where we are unable to get GPS data, the system should initially capture the user's speed. \n         b. Say if user's average speed is 5m/sec and after 30 seconds, we want to trigger GPS query and does not get the result, we would simply do TotalDistance = PreviousDistance + (Speed * Time)\n             which would add 150 metrics (for this scenario) to the last total distance.\n         c. If we were able to get the GPS data, we would proceed with previous calculation of Total Distance = PreviousDistance + (New Lat,Long - Last Lat, Long)\n\n6. How will your system support tracking activities while the users device is offline? \n       a. In case of offline scenarios, App1 should own the responsibility of maintaining the list of non-synced activities in its local DB.\n       b. So, when a user requests for Start/Stop/Pause an activity, local DB should persist that information.\n       c. If the user wants to start a new activity, local DB should also persist that information\n       d. If the App crashes and restarts, the data can be fetched from the local DB in the device. \n       e. So, as soon as the device is online and LastSyncedTimestamp < LastModifiedTimestamp, trigger a sync via the 'Sync' microservice.\n       f. The microservice would be responsible to persist the information in the Server DB.\n\n7. When the device comes back online after an extended offline period, how would you handle the case where the user has modified the same activity on multiple devices, \n      or where the local activity data conflicts with what's already on the server?\n      a. This is a scenario of multiple conflicts and we need a service to resolve conflicts.\n      b. Say a user is operating on multiple devices and both of them is offline. When they come online, the respective apps would sent a request to Sync microservice \n          where each request's LastModifedTimestamp would be different from others. In such scenarios, the microservice should own the responsibility of checking\n          which request's LastModifiedTimestamp is latest and process the single request. For the one that failed, reply back to the App saying something went wrong, please refresh.\n      c. However, if these 2 requests are not fired at the same time, the one which reaches the Sync Microservice first will simply modify the Activity Table.\n      d. Now, when the second request is fired, the Sync Microservice checks if the LastModifiedTimestamp (Of server) == LastSyncedTimestamp (Of localDB) is same. If it is not,\n          that means App2 localDB is not synced and user has added actions on top of them. Ask App2 to resync and then add actions on top of them.\n\n8. How can we support up-to-date sharing of activities with friends while the activity is in progress, not just after completion?\n      a. This seems to be fan-out problem where we want to share the current active activity. In such scenarios, both users and their friends should be connected to the App.\n      b. When the user's app's localDB wants to sync, it will send a request to the Sync microservice. The microservice should own the major responsibility of persisting that \n           information to the DB and then proceed to publish 'RouteLocation', 'DistanceCovered', 'TimeTaken' to Pub/Sub.\n      c. Here, we can have a logic of creating a topic when the user clicks on 'Share Live Stats' button and the Sync Microservice will have the responsibility of publishing to the Pub/Sub.\n      d. Now, friends sitting in App2 or App3 will get a notification to accept the user's live sharing activity. Once accepted, their Sync microservice instances will subscribe to that topic\n          and will not start receiving messages which would be returned by Sync Microservice to App2 and App3.\n      e. All of this connection between App and Sync are bi-directional, hence we would proceed with WebSocket Connection.\n\nAnother approach - Their friends can also periodically poll at a fixed interval to get their friend's data by using GET activity/<UserID>\n     a. Having too many websocket connections would put a lot of load on the CPU resources.\n     b. If live is not instantaneous and we are okay with some amount of delay, we would like to proceed with fixed polling as it is a simple HTTP request \n         and will query the database and would provide the data in real time. It will also help in getting rid of Pub/sub mechanism.\n     c. If the user is a celebrity, we can persist the activity information to a cache with TTL of N + 10 seconds. So, that when a new update comes, \n          we can write to cache again so that other friends/followers can query the cache to reduce the load on database.\n\n9. How can we expose an up-to-date leaderboard of top athletes globally based on the total distance covered?\n     a. When you mention Top athletes, it should be a finite number.\n     b. Since this is a leaderboard, it would be heavily queries and need to sustain a heavy read throughput and near real time latency.\n     c. To satisfy both the constraints, we can have a running cache with Sorted Set based on total Distance Covered.\n     d. To write to the cache, anytime a Sync micoservice updates the DB, it can have a stream which would flow into the cache and update the Sorted Set.\n     d. When an App requests to view the leaderboard, the Stats microservice would read from the cache and return the Top 50-100 athletes.\n\n10. In your Redis Sorted Set approach, how would you handle the scenario where a user retroactively edits a completed activity to correct the distance, and this update needs \n       to be reflected in the global leaderboard? Walk me through the flow from the edit request to the cache update.\n         a. App1 makes a PATCH request to Sync1 service to sync the local DB to the ServerDB, The microservice updates the Activity with the parameters sent. \n         b. The DB recognizes a UPDATE call and trigger a stream (similar to DynamoDB stream - event stream). \n         c. The consumer of the stream could be a serverless Lambda which processes 1 message/sec and call ADD SORTEDSET.\n         d. The SortedSet has an underlying data structure of Red Black Tree which rebalances itself on every insert. Since the set is bounded, the one activity which exceeds the \n              the sorted set size is eliminated.\n",
